WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:17.000
Everyone in their dog is moving to the cloud.

00:17.000 --> 00:20.000
So you'd expect there to be a lot of questions on the exam.

00:20.000 --> 00:37.000
Everyone in their dog is moving to the cloud.

00:37.000 --> 00:41.000
So you'd expect there to be a lot of questions on the exam related to cloud computing.

00:41.000 --> 00:45.000
Because there's one or two security issues involved with moving to the cloud.

00:45.000 --> 00:50.000
And while there will be some questions on the exam related to cloud, there's not a huge amount of them.

00:50.000 --> 00:56.000
And in fact, there's only this one small section in this entire giant course that we're going to talk about cloud computing.

00:56.000 --> 00:58.000
And the reason for that is this.

00:58.000 --> 01:04.000
ISC squared, the organization behind this CISSP exam, made a decision a few years ago.

01:04.000 --> 01:06.000
They were seeing where the industry was going.

01:06.000 --> 01:09.000
They were seeing that everyone was starting to move to the cloud.

01:09.000 --> 01:11.000
And so they had a decision to make.

01:11.000 --> 01:17.000
When they were updating the CISSP exam material, they could start to build in more and more and more cloud material.

01:17.000 --> 01:21.000
Or they could break it out as an entirely different certification.

01:21.000 --> 01:23.000
And that's exactly what they did.

01:23.000 --> 01:29.000
They broke it out into a separate certification, which is the CCSP Certified Cloud Security Professional.

01:29.000 --> 01:32.000
Another one of those courses that we teach.

01:32.000 --> 01:35.000
Another course that we teach.

01:35.000 --> 01:37.000
And the reason that they chose to do this.

01:37.000 --> 01:42.000
And I think it was a good decision, not just that they were trying to make more money on certifications.

01:42.000 --> 01:45.000
There's a lot of intricacies in cloud.

01:45.000 --> 01:47.000
There's a lot of fundamental concepts that you need to understand.

01:47.000 --> 01:53.000
And there's a lot in the governance, the processes, the technicalities of how to properly move to the cloud.

01:53.000 --> 01:59.000
Secure the cloud, know how to have interoperability, portability, be able to remember, have a reversibility, get out of the cloud.

01:59.000 --> 02:01.000
There's a lot of complication here.

02:01.000 --> 02:04.000
And it's more than would reasonably fit in this course.

02:04.000 --> 02:08.000
And so I think it made a lot of sense for them to move that into a separate certification.

02:08.000 --> 02:14.000
And so in this course, the CISSP, I'm going to cover cloud at like the 10,000 or 30,000 foot level.

02:14.000 --> 02:16.000
Very high level, just some of the very basics.

02:16.000 --> 02:19.000
Because you will get a few questions, but not a huge amount of them.

02:19.000 --> 02:24.000
And if you really want to get deep into the cloud computing, go and take something like the CCSP.

02:24.000 --> 02:26.000
So let's get into some of the basics of the cloud.

02:26.000 --> 02:29.000
And let me start by asking you this simple question.

02:29.000 --> 02:31.000
What is the cloud?

02:31.000 --> 02:32.000
Think about this from above.

02:32.000 --> 02:36.000
Trying to find it in very simple, easy to understand terms.

02:36.000 --> 02:41.000
How would you explain it to someone who has never understood the cloud or never thought of it before?

02:41.000 --> 02:43.000
It's actually a bit of a trick question.

02:43.000 --> 02:49.000
It's very difficult to describe what is cloud in very simple terms.

02:49.000 --> 02:53.000
And the reason is this, cloud is many, many different things to many different people.

02:53.000 --> 02:56.000
It can be systems running in your own data center.

02:56.000 --> 02:59.000
It can be systems running in another service provider's data center.

03:00.000 --> 03:03.000
It can be everything from, you know, creating an entire virtual data center

03:03.000 --> 03:08.000
to just doing identity access management or security as a service or database as a service.

03:08.000 --> 03:12.000
There is so many things that fall under the umbrella of cloud.

03:12.000 --> 03:19.000
What the industry has settled on is rather than trying to come up with a nice, simple, concise definition of cloud, which is impossible.

03:19.000 --> 03:23.000
Instead, what we use is a set of defining characteristics.

03:23.000 --> 03:27.000
There's five primary and a sixth kind of characteristic.

03:27.000 --> 03:32.000
That if a service complies with these characteristics, then you can call it cloud.

03:32.000 --> 03:35.000
So let's spend a few minutes going through those characteristics.

03:35.000 --> 03:39.000
And it starts to help explain a little bit of what cloud actually is.

03:39.000 --> 03:43.000
The first characteristic is on-demand self-service.

03:43.000 --> 03:49.000
And this is the idea that if you are using cloud, you can request cloud services by yourself.

03:49.000 --> 03:51.000
And you can do it whenever you want.

03:51.000 --> 03:54.000
Nowadays, what does it actually take to request cloud services?

03:54.000 --> 03:57.000
Well, for free stuff, you can just sign up for free.

03:57.000 --> 04:00.000
Things like Gmail and box and all these sorts of things.

04:00.000 --> 04:04.000
These are big cloud services that you need nothing more than maybe an email address to sign up for.

04:04.000 --> 04:08.000
And even the paid services, all you really need is a credit card number.

04:08.000 --> 04:11.000
And this is a really important defining characteristic of cloud.

04:11.000 --> 04:14.000
Because a lot of organizations nowadays, they want to fail fast.

04:14.000 --> 04:17.000
They want to innovate. They want to rapidly try things out.

04:17.000 --> 04:21.000
And that's very difficult to do in a traditional environment where,

04:21.000 --> 04:27.000
if a lot of my clients, I ask them, how long does it take you to get a new server provision in your environment?

04:27.000 --> 04:33.000
And it's not uncommon for someone to say weeks, maybe even months, two, three months, to get a new server provisioned.

04:33.000 --> 04:36.000
If you're trying to rapidly innovate, fail fast.

04:36.000 --> 04:41.000
It's pretty hard to do that if you're waiting two or three months just for a server to be set up.

04:41.000 --> 04:45.000
And so one of the really, really valuable things of cloud on-demand self-service,

04:45.000 --> 04:49.000
you can sign up for an unbelievable amount of services, terabytes of storage,

04:49.000 --> 04:54.000
machine learning algorithms, vision APIs, all sorts of crazy stuff.

04:54.000 --> 04:57.000
And all you need is clicking a couple of those buttons.

04:57.000 --> 05:01.000
And it all happens instantaneously or nearly so.

05:01.000 --> 05:03.000
Lost my pointer. There we go.

05:03.000 --> 05:05.000
So that's the first characteristic of cloud.

05:05.000 --> 05:08.000
The next one is what is known as broad network access.

05:08.000 --> 05:15.000
And what this characteristic is about is from where and what type of devices can you access the cloud.

05:15.000 --> 05:18.000
Most cloud services are web-based applications.

05:18.000 --> 05:23.000
And most cloud is public cloud or software as a service in the public cloud.

05:23.000 --> 05:29.000
Which means that the vast majority of the way that we access the cloud is through a web browser across the internet.

05:29.000 --> 05:33.000
And everything has a web browser installed in it nowadays.

05:33.000 --> 05:37.000
I was at Home Depot recently and I was browsing the internet on a fridge.

05:37.000 --> 05:42.000
So on-demand self-service means you can essentially access most of these cloud services from anywhere in the world.

05:42.000 --> 05:46.000
Because most cloud services are accessed through a web browser.

05:47.000 --> 05:50.000
Now the next characteristic resource pooling.

05:50.000 --> 05:52.000
This is where we need to spend a few minutes on this one.

05:52.000 --> 05:54.000
This one is really critical.

05:54.000 --> 05:58.000
There are three primary resources that we pool share in the cloud.

05:58.000 --> 06:02.000
Compute network and storage.

06:02.000 --> 06:08.000
And when we say we pool or we share these resources, what we're saying is that as a customer in the cloud,

06:08.000 --> 06:11.000
you can get access to compute computers, you know, like a CPU essentially.

06:11.000 --> 06:13.000
It allows you to do problem solving.

06:13.000 --> 06:14.000
You can get access to network.

06:14.000 --> 06:18.000
The ability to move bits around between your different systems, databases, and so forth.

06:18.000 --> 06:21.000
And storage, which allows you to store the bits.

06:21.000 --> 06:24.000
In the cloud, you can get access to all three of these resources.

06:24.000 --> 06:29.000
But very importantly, your access to all of these resources is virtualized.

06:29.000 --> 06:36.000
You do not have direct physical access to a hard drive to a CPU to the network.

06:36.000 --> 06:39.000
Your access to all of these services is virtualized.

06:39.000 --> 06:41.000
There's a layer of abstraction.

06:41.000 --> 06:46.000
Which allows all of these resources to be shared across cloud customers.

06:46.000 --> 06:48.000
What's the advantage of this?

06:48.000 --> 06:50.000
Because there's a big one.

06:50.000 --> 06:52.000
Let me ask you this.

06:52.000 --> 06:57.000
In a traditional data center, if you were to look at an average server, like the payroll server,

06:57.000 --> 07:02.000
what would the average utilization be of an average server in a well-run data center?

07:02.000 --> 07:06.000
The answer is usually somewhere in the range to 10 to 20%.

07:06.000 --> 07:09.000
So you take this very expensive piece of hardware, a server,

07:09.000 --> 07:15.000
and you're only utilizing 10 to 20% of the resources on that server, on average.

07:15.000 --> 07:19.000
It's a very inefficient use of that and very expensive hardware.

07:19.000 --> 07:22.000
And any well-run data center is like this traditional data center.

07:22.000 --> 07:24.000
Why?

07:24.000 --> 07:28.000
Well, it's because you don't size a server based on average utilization.

07:28.000 --> 07:32.000
You size a server based on peak utilization.

07:32.000 --> 07:34.000
And so take the payroll server as an example.

07:34.000 --> 07:37.000
The vast majority of this time, what's the payroll server doing?

07:37.000 --> 07:38.000
Not much.

07:38.000 --> 07:42.000
Once in a while someone might log in to like pay you less or something, but that's it.

07:42.000 --> 07:46.000
But then once every two weeks or once a month, what's the payroll server do?

07:46.000 --> 07:48.000
It runs the payroll batch job.

07:48.000 --> 07:51.000
And then for that period of time, you know, your CPU usage, your RAM usage,

07:51.000 --> 07:53.000
it's spiked, max utilization.

07:53.000 --> 07:56.000
And then you go back to doing almost nothing.

07:56.000 --> 07:59.000
So in a traditional data center, we're only getting, you know,

07:59.000 --> 08:02.000
we're only using 10 to 20% of the capacity of our systems.

08:02.000 --> 08:04.000
Very inefficient.

08:04.000 --> 08:08.000
Now in the public and the cloud, especially the public cloud,

08:08.000 --> 08:14.000
because access to resources virtualized, it allows us to share those resources.

08:14.000 --> 08:17.000
So in the cloud, we don't have what's typically what's called a server.

08:17.000 --> 08:18.000
You have a compute node.

08:18.000 --> 08:20.000
A compute node is essentially a server.

08:20.000 --> 08:25.000
It's a CPU and a SRAM on top of which you can run virtual machines.

08:25.000 --> 08:30.000
And these virtual machines are accessing the compute resources of this compute node.

08:30.000 --> 08:35.000
Now in the cloud, because you can share this compute node across multiple clients,

08:35.000 --> 08:40.000
you can run multiple virtual machines simultaneously on top of a hypervisor,

08:40.000 --> 08:42.000
which is on top of the compute node.

08:42.000 --> 08:47.000
And so these multiple virtual machines can share the underlying hardware,

08:47.000 --> 08:51.000
which allows you to put a whole bunch of different virtual machines,

08:51.000 --> 08:56.000
virtual servers on top of one compute node, and get much better resource utilization

08:56.000 --> 08:58.000
of that underlying hardware.

08:58.000 --> 09:03.000
Because each of those virtual servers might only be running along at 10 to 20% capacity,

09:03.000 --> 09:04.000
something like that.

09:04.000 --> 09:06.000
But if you put enough of them onto a compute node,

09:06.000 --> 09:09.000
the overall resource usage of the compute node,

09:09.000 --> 09:12.000
the underlying physical hardware, what's that?

09:12.000 --> 09:16.000
Well, in the cloud, it's not uncommon to achieve resource utilization of 70, 80,

09:16.000 --> 09:19.000
maybe even 90% of the underlying hardware.

09:19.000 --> 09:22.000
So traditional data sender, you're getting like 10 to 20% utilization of the hardware.

09:22.000 --> 09:27.000
In the cloud, you might be achieving 70, 80% utilization of the underlying hardware.

09:27.000 --> 09:30.000
So much more effective use of the underlying hardware,

09:30.000 --> 09:35.000
because you can virtualize, share the access amongst customers.

09:35.000 --> 09:38.000
And I'll add one other piece to this that really helps drive down the costs.

09:38.000 --> 09:43.000
When you look at what the big cloud providers and how much hardware they buy,

09:43.000 --> 09:45.000
it is astronomical.

09:45.000 --> 09:49.000
They buy a huge number of hard drives of CPUs, of network devices.

09:49.000 --> 09:52.000
And so as a result, the prices that they're paying for that hardware

09:52.000 --> 09:56.000
is, you know, economies of scale much lower than a traditional company

09:56.000 --> 09:58.000
could typically buy stuff for.

09:58.000 --> 10:01.000
Like when you look at the Amazon, the Google's, the Facebook's,

10:01.000 --> 10:05.000
the Azure Microsoft of the world, they buy hardware at staggering levels.

10:05.000 --> 10:09.000
They're spending billions of dollars every year building out their data centers,

10:09.000 --> 10:12.000
which means they get economies of scale that no one else can achieve.

10:12.000 --> 10:17.000
And that makes the underlying costs of the compute network and storage

10:17.000 --> 10:21.000
and the cloud much cheaper than what you can traditionally achieve

10:21.000 --> 10:24.000
in a traditional data center.

10:24.000 --> 10:27.000
But I'll caveat that with one very important thing.

10:27.000 --> 10:30.000
And my experience working with a lot of companies that move to the cloud,

10:30.000 --> 10:33.000
they're overall costs moving to the cloud have not actually been cheaper.

10:33.000 --> 10:37.000
The underlying resources and compute network and storage are cheaper.

10:37.000 --> 10:40.000
But when you layer on top of all the additional services that you need,

10:40.000 --> 10:42.000
it can often end up being a lot more expensive.

10:42.000 --> 10:44.000
That's a discussion for another course.

10:44.000 --> 10:46.000
But that's resource pooling.

10:46.000 --> 10:50.000
You share compute network and storage across multiple customers.

10:51.000 --> 10:55.000
Now, next one, rapid elasticity and scalability.

10:55.000 --> 10:59.000
What this means is that in the cloud, you can rapidly, quickly increase

10:59.000 --> 11:02.000
your, your use of compute network and storage.

11:02.000 --> 11:06.000
If you suddenly want hundreds of new virtual CPUs to run something on top of,

11:06.000 --> 11:10.000
done. If you want a petabyte of storage, done.

11:10.000 --> 11:13.000
If you want tons and more network bandwidth, done.

11:13.000 --> 11:16.000
And this again is very different than traditional data center.

11:16.000 --> 11:18.000
Let's say in a traditional data center, you're like,

11:18.000 --> 11:20.000
you know what, I want a petabyte of storage.

11:20.000 --> 11:23.000
So you call up EMC, takes them a month or two,

11:23.000 --> 11:26.000
but they ship out a few trucks worth of hard drives and storage race servers.

11:26.000 --> 11:28.000
And you spend another month setting all this stuff up.

11:28.000 --> 11:30.000
And now you've got your petabyte of storage.

11:30.000 --> 11:33.000
And then you're like, nah, you know what, I don't need any more.

11:33.000 --> 11:36.000
Too bad, you bought it. It's yours now, right?

11:36.000 --> 11:40.000
Whereas in the cloud, rapid elasticity means you can quickly increase

11:40.000 --> 11:43.000
your utilization of any of the compute network and storage.

11:43.000 --> 11:46.000
And just as rapidly decrease your utilization.

11:46.000 --> 11:48.000
So rapid elasticity.

11:48.000 --> 11:52.000
And care closely tied to this is what's known as measured service,

11:52.000 --> 11:56.000
which is the cloud service provider carefully measures your usage of the cloud,

11:56.000 --> 11:59.000
how much compute you're using, how much network, how much storage,

11:59.000 --> 12:01.000
and you only pay for what you use.

12:01.000 --> 12:05.000
And so if you're only using that petabyte of storage for 10 minutes,

12:05.000 --> 12:09.000
you're only paying for that petabyte of storage for 10 minutes.

12:09.000 --> 12:13.000
So those are the five defining characteristics of cloud.

12:13.000 --> 12:16.000
And if you get any questions asking you what are the five defining characteristics,

12:16.000 --> 12:18.000
that's them.

12:18.000 --> 12:22.000
But there's sometimes a sixth characteristic that's put in there.

12:22.000 --> 12:25.000
And it's known as multi-tenancy.

12:25.000 --> 12:30.000
And the reason that's not always in the list is because it's not always true.

12:30.000 --> 12:33.000
There's one major difference between public cloud and private cloud.

12:33.000 --> 12:36.000
Public cloud is accessible usable by anyone.

12:36.000 --> 12:38.000
So therefore it is multi-tenancy.

12:38.000 --> 12:44.000
But private cloud is reserved only accessible by one consumer.

12:44.000 --> 12:47.000
Therefore, not multi-tenancy.

12:47.000 --> 12:49.000
The majority of cloud is public cloud.

12:49.000 --> 12:51.000
So the majority of cloud is multi-tenancy.

12:51.000 --> 12:52.000
But not all of it.

12:52.000 --> 12:55.000
We'll talk about the different deployment models in the next video.

12:55.000 --> 12:59.000
We'll talk about public, private, community, and hybrid cloud.

12:59.000 --> 13:02.000
But that's why multi-tenancy doesn't apply everywhere.

13:08.000 --> 13:10.000
Thank you very much.

